  "text": "Django's migration squashing compliance system is implemented across multiple interconnected modules in the django/db/migrations package and management commands.\n\n**Squash Migration Generator**: The squashmigrations command (django/core/management/commands/squashmigrations.py:Command.handle) is the primary entry point for generating squashed migrations. It collects all migration operations between a start and end migration, optimizes them using MigrationOptimizer, and creates a new migration instance with a replaces attribute that lists all replaced migrations. The command then writes the new migration file using MigrationWriter.\n\n**Replaced Migrations Tracking**: The Migration class (django/db/migrations/migration.py:Migration) defines a replaces attribute that lists migrations being replaced. The MigrationLoader (django/db/migrations/loader.py) manages replaced migration tracking through three key methods: (1) replace_migration() processes each replacing migration recursively and determines whether to apply the replacement or not based on whether all replaced migrations are either applied or unapplied; (2) _resolve_replaced_migration_keys() recursively resolves migration keys to find the ultimate migration targets; (3) all_replaced_applied() checks if all migrations in a replace chain have been applied. The MigrationRecorder (django/db/migrations/recorder.py:MigrationRecorder.record_applied and record_unapplied) tracks which migrations are in the applied state in the database. The MigrationExecutor (django/db/migrations/executor.py:MigrationExecutor.record_migration) records both the squashed migration and each of its replaced migrations when applied, and check_replacements() marks replacement migrations as applied when all their replaced migrations are applied.\n\n**Dependency Graph Validation**: The MigrationGraph (django/db/migrations/graph.py) implements critical validation logic: (1) validate_consistency() ensures no dummy nodes (representing missing/unresolved dependencies) remain in the graph after all migrations are loaded; (2) ensure_not_cyclic() uses a depth-first search algorithm to detect circular dependencies; (3) remove_replaced_nodes() updates the dependency graph by remapping all parent and child references from replaced migrations to the replacement migration while avoiding self-references; (4) remove_replacement_node() performs the inverse operation when a partially-applied squashed migration must be removed. The loader's build_graph() method calls these validation methods after adding all migrations to ensure consistency.\n\n**Squash Completeness Check**: The MigrationLoader.check_consistent_history() method validates that all applied migrations have their dependencies satisfied - if a migration is applied but its parent dependencies aren't, it raises InconsistentMigrationHistory. This check includes special handling for replaced migrations via all_replaced_applied() which allows skipping unapplied squashed migrations if all their replaced migrations are applied.\n\n**Supporting Components**: The MigrationOptimizer (django/db/migrations/optimizer.py:MigrationOptimizer.optimize) reduces the number of operations in squashed migrations by combining compatible operations. The MigrationWriter (django/db/migrations/writer.py:MigrationWriter.as_string) serializes the squashed migration with its replaces attribute into the migration file format. The optimizemigration command (django/core/management/commands/optimizemigration.py) allows further optimization of individual migrations. The exceptions module (django/db/migrations/exceptions.py) defines NodeNotFoundError, CircularDependencyError, and InconsistentMigrationHistory which are raised during validation failures."
}

